order of operations in the `production` stage. We will perform all the file copying and `npm` installation steps as `root`, and then, as a final step before execution, change the ownership of all the files to `appuser` and switch to that user. This is a secure and common pattern.\n\nHere are the necessary changes for your `Dockerfile`:\n\n```diff\n--- a/home/perrymckay1/Dockerfile\n+++ b/home/perrymckay1/Dockerfile\n@@ -27,20 +27,21 @@\n # Create and use a non-root user for better security\n RUN addgroup -S appgroup \u0026\u0026 adduser -S appuser -G appgroup\n-USER appuser\n \n # Copy package files and install *only* production dependencies\n+# We'll do this as root, which is fine for a build step.\n COPY package.json package-lock.json* ./\n RUN npm ci --omit=dev\n \n # Copy the built assets and necessary source code from the builder stage\n COPY --from=builder /usr/src/app/dist ./dist\n COPY --from=builder /usr/src/app/src ./src\n \n+# Now, change ownership of all application files to the non-root user\n+RUN chown -R appuser:appgroup /usr/src/app\n+\n+# Switch to the non-root user for execution\n+USER appuser\n+\n # Expose the port your application will run on\n EXPOSE 3000\n \n # The command to start your application in production\n-CMD [\"node\", \"src/index.js\"] # Or whatever your entry point is\n+CMD [\"node\", \"src/index.js\"]\n\n```\n\nWith these changes, your `docker build` command should complete successfully without any errors or warnings. You can now build and run your container as before.\n\n\u003c!--\n[PROMPT_SUGGESTION]How can I use Docker Compose to manage my environment variables and run the container?[/PROMPT_SUGGESTION]\n[PROMPT_SUGGESTION]Explain the security benefits of using a non-root user in the Dockerfile.[/PROMPT_SUGGESTION]\n--\u003e","chatSectionId":"1","promptCitations":[{"startIndex":1522,"endIndex":1710,"filepath":"/home/perrymckay1/Dockerfile","citationText":"Create and use a non-root user for better security\n RUN addgroup -S appgr